==English==

===Etymology===
First attested [[w:1393|1393]], from {{etyl|la}} ''[[simile#Latin|simile]]'' ("comparison, likeness", "parallel"), originally from ''[[simile#Latin|simile]]'' the neuter form of ''[[similis]]'' ("like, similar, resembling"). Confer the English ''[[similar]]''.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈsɪməli/}}
* {{audio|en-us-simile.ogg|Audio (US)}}
{{examples-right|sense=figure of speech|examples=“A woman needs a man like a fish needs a bicycle.”<br>[[w:Irina Dunn|Irina Dunn]] (1970)}}
===Noun===
{{en-noun|pl2=similia}}

# A [[figure of speech]] in which one thing is compared to another, in the case of English generally using ''like'' or ''as''.
#: ''A '''simile''' is like a metaphor.''

